## 5. Edit Behavior Rules

### 5.1 Field-Level Edit Mode

Each editable field has an edit icon (pencil) that appears on hover in read mode. Clicking it converts that field to an input. All other fields remain in read mode.

When a field is in edit mode:
- The field becomes an input (text, textarea, dropdown — matching the original creation form input type)
- Two inline controls appear below the field: `Save` and `Cancel`
- `Save` commits the change, exits edit mode, writes the update, and logs the change
- `Cancel` discards the change and returns to read mode — no log entry

### 5.2 Which Fields Are Editable

**Always editable (any time after creation):**
- Initiative name
- Owner
- Target Completion
- Status
- Labels
- Known Constraints (Prioritize)
- Binary Done Definition (Plant)
- Signal to Watch (Iterate)
- Time Box (Iterate)

**Editable with change prompt (see Section 5.3):**
- Outcome statement (Prioritize)
- Sprint connection — why this sprint (Prioritize)
- What this unlocks (Plant)
- What already exists (Iterate)
- Adjustment definition (Iterate)

**Not editable after creation:**
- Capability link — the initiative is bound to its capability. Moving an initiative to a different capability is a deliberate structural decision handled separately via a `Move to [column]` action, not a field edit.
- Tier assignment — same logic. Tier changes are structural, not field edits.

### 5.3 Change Prompt for Outcome-Level Edits

When a founder saves a change to any field in the "editable with change prompt" category, a lightweight inline prompt appears immediately after save:

*"What prompted this change? (Optional)"*

A single short text input. Two actions: `Add context` (saves the note alongside the change log entry) and `Skip` (dismisses — the change is still logged, just without a note).

This is dismissable. It should never feel like a required step. It surfaces once per save event, then disappears. The founder can skip it every time if they choose.

